  </div>
  <div class="comment-content">
    <p>Ahhh, NeXT. That was a cool effing box. What was it, a 40 MHz 68040? No! I checked Wikipedia (always reliable) and the first NeXT cube apparently had a 25 MHz 68030. Considering this was 1988, that was pretty good. (And again, a correction. According to Wikipedia, it came out in 1990.) The second generation had the '040, and was actually cheaper than the first round, which is good, as they were not cheap.</p>

<p>In my estimation, you cannot call NeXT a failure. Tim Berners-Lee used one to create the Web, the same thing most people consider to be the Internets. And the NeXT OS, NeXTSTEP, went on to become the basis of Mac OS X. And that actually is going pretty darn well.</p>
  </div>
</div>

  

  
  

