<div class="comment" id="comment-229825">
  <span class="comment-moderate"> <a href='http://dynamic.boingboing.net/cgi-bin/mt/plugins/Moderate/moderate.cgi?__mode=flag&comment_id=229825&rnd=591314' title='Take a look at this' onClick="return moderate(this, 'http://dynamic.boingboing.net/cgi-bin/mt/plugins/Moderate/moderate.cgi?__mode=flag&comment_id=229825&rnd=591314'); return false;">Take a look at this</a></span>
  <div class="comment-header">
  <span class="comment-id">#9</span> posted by <a href="http://dynamic.boingboing.net/profile/dculberson">dculberson</a>  , <a href="#comment-229825" title="Permalink to this comment">July  9, 2008  6:44 PM</a>
  </div>
  <div class="comment-content">
    <p>I actually had an '040 Turbo NeXT Dimension cube and a turbo slab a little while back.. I sold the cube to a friend and gave him the slab as a bonus.  They're still incredible looking and feeling machines; the casing on the cube is magnesium, and the monitor base is magnesium.  The build quality of the whole thing is incredible.  I even had a couple matching laser printers; even the <i>paper trays</i> matched the design aesthetic.  Hell, everything down to the freakin' power cords matched!!  (Logos, black, with little ribs, etc..)  So cool.  One of the highlights of computer history, for sure.</p>

<p>And most certainly not a failure.  Unless you mean failure as in not around any more.  But they definitely contributed to the improvement of computers as a whole.</p>
  </div>
</div>

  
